# Safety, Fire, and Ergonomics Engineering

## Overview

My activities in safety engineering span professional engineering practice, applied research, technical analysis, and academic investigation.

Over several decades, I have worked on real-world engineering problems involving fire protection, occupational safety, ergonomics, regulatory requirements, and technical risk assessment. This professional trajectory includes dozens of engineering projects and technical activities formally registered through Brazilian Engineering Responsibility Records (ART – *Anotação de Responsabilidade Técnica*).

A central characteristic of this work is the integration of engineering practice with technical and scientific investigation. Problems identified in professional environments have frequently motivated research on fire safety, regulatory systems, equipment selection, ergonomics, and risk.

---

## Fire Protection and Fire Safety Engineering

A significant part of my engineering activities has been dedicated to fire protection and fire safety.

My technical and research work has addressed fire extinguishers, fire protection equipment, extinguishing capacity, equipment selection criteria, fire risks, regulatory requirements, and the technical consequences of changes in Brazilian fire safety regulations.

Particular attention has been given to the distinction between regulatory compliance and effective engineering safety. Several studies have investigated situations in which apparently straightforward regulatory or equipment-selection criteria may introduce technical limitations or unintended risks.

---

## Fire Extinguishers, Regulation, and Technical Analysis

Fire extinguisher technology and regulation constitute a long-standing area of professional and research activity.

Studies have examined the organizational impacts of INMETRO regulations on fire extinguisher maintenance companies, the technical and environmental implications of disposable ABC vehicle fire extinguishers, and the evolution of Brazilian traffic regulations concerning fire extinguishers in motor vehicles.

More recent investigations have focused on the risks of using extinguishing capacity as an isolated criterion for extinguisher selection and on the engineering implications of replacing pressurized-water extinguishers with multipurpose dry chemical extinguishers.

This research combines equipment technology, fire behavior, regulation, and engineering judgment.

---

## Occupational Safety and Applied Engineering Practice

My professional activities in occupational safety include technical assessments, risk analysis, engineering projects, and applied investigations developed in different work environments.

These activities are grounded in practical engineering problems and in the systematic evaluation of hazards, work processes, equipment, and regulatory requirements.

Over the years, dozens of technical engineering activities and projects in safety-related fields have been formally developed under ART professional responsibility records.

This practical background strongly influences my research approach: engineering problems are examined not only from a regulatory perspective, but also in terms of physical mechanisms, operational conditions, human interaction, and actual risk.

---

## Ergonomics and Human–Technology Interaction

My research in ergonomics has addressed both occupational activities and the interaction between users, tools, and technical systems.

One study investigated the manual pressurization of portable fire extinguisher cylinders, examining the ergonomic characteristics of an industrial work activity.

Another research line addressed the ergodesign of an endodontic file associated with dental floss during root canal instrumentation, extending ergonomic analysis toward human–tool interaction and product design.

These studies reflect a multidisciplinary approach to ergonomics, connecting work analysis, engineering, design, and human interaction with technical artifacts.

---

## Fire and Evacuation Modeling

My experience in fire and safety engineering also contributed to research on emergency evacuation and computational analysis of occupant movement.

This research direction later led to the development of **FUGA**, a computational framework for microscopic evacuation simulation and the analysis of emergency egress scenarios.

The FUGA research and software development cycle is presented separately.

